# NB: Control Structures and Functions

## `if`/`else` Statements

You've seen this in Python.

They work the same way in both languages.

Here's their syntax in R.

```         
if(<condition>) {
        ## do something
} 

if(<condition>) {
        ## do something
} 
else {
        ## do something else
}

if(<condition1>) {
        ## do something
} else if(<condition2>)  {
        ## do something different
} else {
        ## do something different
}
```

Generate a uniform random number:


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-2_8d3cdd3bc2af9e71db8ed4237927f0ab'}

```{.r .cell-code}
x <- runif(1, 0, 10) # From the Uniform Distribution

if(x > 3) {
  y <- 10
} else {
  y <- 0
}

x
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 8.316552
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
y
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 10
```
:::
:::


You assign an `if` statement to a variable.


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-4_972874c0679ddd7aa5291b9432a2108a'}

```{.r .cell-code}
z <- if(x > 3) {
  10
} else { 
  0
}

z
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 10
```
:::
:::


You can stack `if` blocks, too.

```         
if(<condition1>) {

}

if(<condition2>) {

}
```

## Control Structures

### `for` Loops

For loops are straight-forward. The take an interator variable, e.g.
`i`, and assign it successive values from a sequence or vector.

For loops are often used to iteratE over the elements of an object
(list, vector, etc.).


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-6_9739b399921ec0d7ebfc6cce203db6b4'}

```{.r .cell-code}
for(i in 1:10) {
  print(i)
}
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 1
[1] 2
[1] 3
[1] 4
[1] 5
[1] 6
[1] 7
[1] 8
[1] 9
[1] 10
```
:::
:::


According to Hadley Wickham, loops are pretty much the only looping
construct that you will need in R.

The following three loops all have the same behavior.


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-8_d8df42f5477b91c234c00b77a2d2c2af'}

```{.r .cell-code}
x <- c("a", "b", "c", "d")
for (i in 1:4) {
  # Print out each element of 'x'
  print(x[i])  
}
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] "a"
[1] "b"
[1] "c"
[1] "d"
```
:::
:::


### `seq_along()`

The `seq_along()` function is commonly used in conjunction with for
loops in order to generate an integer sequence based on the length of an
object (in this case, the object x).


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-10_30e5a0941aef5ba0edace83234baae50'}

```{.r .cell-code}
x
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] "a" "b" "c" "d"
```
:::
:::


Generate a sequence based on length of 'x':


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-12_7843aa3179374208cb5bed0e1d2ab81a'}

```{.r .cell-code}
for(i in seq_along(x)) {   
  print(x[i])
}
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] "a"
[1] "b"
[1] "c"
[1] "d"
```
:::
:::


It is not necessary to use an index-type variable.


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-14_4bad7492f8fd31249499597ac074078c'}

```{.r .cell-code}
for(letter in x) {
  print(letter)
}
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] "a"
[1] "b"
[1] "c"
[1] "d"
```
:::
:::


For one line loops, the curly braces are not strictly necessary.


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-16_3661df3d92d8c042ad66046c07a0e4d1'}

```{.r .cell-code}
for(i in 1:4) print(x[i])
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] "a"
[1] "b"
[1] "c"
[1] "d"
```
:::
:::


### Nested `for` loops

Dor loops can be nested inside of each other.


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-18_316b49964708d52b567c0be427b2c9bb'}

```{.r .cell-code}
x <- matrix(1:6, 2, 3)
for(i in seq_len(nrow(x))) {
  for(j in seq_len(ncol(x))) {
    print(x[i, j])
  }   
}
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 1
[1] 3
[1] 5
[1] 2
[1] 4
[1] 6
```
:::
:::


Nested loops are used to generate multidimensional or hierarchical data
structures (e.g. matrices, lists).

## `while` Loops

As with Python, while loops start with a condition. It loops while the
condition is true and stops when it is false.

Remembe, while loops can go on forever is the truth condition is never
met.


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-20_719baeee15bf341a602928f5334e1f60'}

```{.r .cell-code}
count <- 0
while(count < 10) {
  print(count)
  count <- count + 1
}
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 0
[1] 1
[1] 2
[1] 3
[1] 4
[1] 5
[1] 6
[1] 7
[1] 8
[1] 9
```
:::
:::


## `repeat` Loops

`repeat` loops are using by R. They initiate an infinite loop right from
the start.

The only way to exit a repeat loop is to call break on an internal
condition.





## `next` and `break`

next is used to skip an iteration of a loop. Same as Python `continue`.


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-24_8f88ab8ace9e20efc0363e949ba1accf'}

```{.r .cell-code}
for (i in 1:100) {
  if (i <= 20) {
    # Skip the first 20 iterations
    next                
  }      # Do something here
}
```
:::


`break` is used to exit a loop immediately.


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-26_1b5c1461477410025d397bb77051576e'}

```{.r .cell-code}
for (i in 1:100) {
  print(i)
  if (i > 20) {
    # Stop loop after 20 iterations
    break  
  }     
}
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 1
[1] 2
[1] 3
[1] 4
[1] 5
[1] 6
[1] 7
[1] 8
[1] 9
[1] 10
[1] 11
[1] 12
[1] 13
[1] 14
[1] 15
[1] 16
[1] 17
[1] 18
[1] 19
[1] 20
[1] 21
```
:::
:::


## Functions

Define some data


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-28_843230a8a60b8e14972fb45ef4f06d49'}

```{.r .cell-code}
x <- 5                
xx <- c(4, 6, 7, 8, 2, 11)
```
:::


Now, define a function that does the following: - takes a value, vector
of values as inputs - normalizes the value against the vector by
subtracting the vector mean from value, and dividing by vector standard
deviation.


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-30_a979d9654d7b06a67e475186b9f8ed8e'}

```{.r .cell-code}
compute_zscore <- function(val, vec) {
  z <- (val - mean(vec)) / sd(vec)
}

print(compute_zscore(x, xx))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] -0.4244764
```
:::
:::


If vector contains identical values, `sd` is zero, and so the z-score is
undefined.


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-32_8855753292e6f57185bbdf9ec0324b9f'}

```{.r .cell-code}
print(compute_zscore(x, c(1, 1, 1, 1)))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] Inf
```
:::
:::


If vector contains missing values, the result will be `NA`.


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-34_1966a3ae3da18df1fce26dc65a43df9a'}

```{.r .cell-code}
xx_na <- c(1, NA, 3, 5) 
print(compute_zscore(x, xx_na))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] NA
```
:::
:::


## Using conditions in functions

A function returns 1 if passed value is odd, 0 if even

## %% is mod operator (returns remainder)


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-36_f78285d34006f114469b54acb51d6897'}

```{.r .cell-code}
is_odd <- function(x){ if (x %% 2 == 1) { 
    return(1) 
  } else { 
    return(0)
  } 
}
```
:::


Call to test some cases:


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-38_aaf11e7bffa6c61a67ec5a298179ed8c'}

```{.r .cell-code}
is_odd(4)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 0
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
is_odd(3)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 1
```
:::
:::


Function arguments can use default values:


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-40_e50c251f81943160bf6c92ee69c17da6'}

```{.r .cell-code}
threshold_vals <- function(p, thresh = 0.5) {
  # for each element in p, returns TRUE if value > thresh, else FALSE
  p > thresh
}
```
:::

::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-42_ceac42699d70b95d2c914f07b234c98f'}

```{.r .cell-code}
threshold_vals(c(0.6, 0.4, 0.1, 1))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1]  TRUE FALSE FALSE  TRUE
```
:::
:::


Now, pass a threshhold:


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-44_4ccf3dad2f3f2678a2023f7826d7bda5'}

```{.r .cell-code}
threshold_vals(c(0.6, 0.4, 0.1, 1), 0.7)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE
```
:::
:::


Assert important preconditions


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-46_5f31beb1252d5cc2a2a055b1302213de'}

```{.r .cell-code}
add_vectors <- function(x, y) {
  # assert the lengths of vectors x and y match
  # if they do, sum elementwise, else throw error with stop()

  if (length(x) != length(y)) {
    stop("x and y must be the same length", call. = FALSE)
  }
  x + y
}
```
:::

::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-48_f4a11be8909f435b15070655a56ca49a'}

```{.r .cell-code}
add_vectors(c(1, 2, 3), c(3, 3, 3))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 4 5 6
```
:::
:::

::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-50_ac2139491cbe2b7a5d5f83a755d218ac'}

```{.r .cell-code}
add_vectors(c(1, 2, 3), c(3, 3, 3, 3)) # breaks
```
:::


## Scoping Rules


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-52_93750b530e3828a90283cd8b4bb1c426'}

```{.r .cell-code}
z <- 4
test_fcn <- function(x) {
  x^z
}
```
:::


Now look at this:


::: {.cell hash='M10-02-ControlStructuresAndFunctions_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-54_f9e39efc7eb8980977696aa255d9fcd5'}

```{.r .cell-code}
test_fcn(2)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 16
```
:::
:::


If `z` isn't defined in the function, how does this work?

R's scoping rules are similar to Python's.

Since `z` isn't in the function, **R looks in the function's
environment** for it.

For more on scoping rules, see [Chapter 15: Scoping Rules of
R](https://bookdown.org/rdpeng/rprogdatascience/scoping-rules-of-r.html)
in Peng's *R Programming For Data Science*.
